{"parse":{"title":"Berklee method","pageid":31168107,"revid":853534961,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In music <a href=\"/wiki/Performance\" title=\"Performance\">performance</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Music_education\" title=\"Music education\">education</a>, the <b>Berklee method</b> is the <a href=\"/wiki/Music_theory\" title=\"Music theory\">music theory</a>, terminology, and practice taught at <a href=\"/wiki/Berklee_College_of_Music\" title=\"Berklee College of Music\">Berklee College of Music</a>, the largest independent college of contemporary music in the world. The \"Berklee method\" was founded by <a href=\"/wiki/Lawrence_Berk\" title=\"Lawrence Berk\">Lawrence Berk</a> after study with <a href=\"/wiki/Joseph_Schillinger\" title=\"Joseph Schillinger\">Joseph Schillinger</a> regarding the latter's, \"elaborate <a href=\"/wiki/Schillinger_System\" title=\"Schillinger System\">system</a> of composition that employed mathematical <a href=\"/wiki/Permutation_(music)\" title=\"Permutation (music)\">permutation</a> and combination process to generate <a href=\"/wiki/Rhythm\" title=\"Rhythm\">rhythms</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Harmony\" title=\"Harmony\">harmonies</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Melody\" title=\"Melody\">melodies</a>\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Later, attempting to codify <a href=\"/wiki/Jazz\" title=\"Jazz\">jazz</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Popular_music\" title=\"Popular music\">popular music</a> practice, the Berklee method often differs from <a href=\"/wiki/Common_practice\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Common practice\">common practice</a> harmony and <a href=\"/wiki/Voice-leading\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Voice-leading\">voice-leading</a> rules or guidelines.\n</p><p>For example, <i>Berklee Music Theory - Book 2</i> recommends the following <a href=\"/wiki/Accompaniment\" title=\"Accompaniment\">accompaniment</a> for a given <a href=\"/wiki/Lead_sheet\" title=\"Lead sheet\">lead sheet</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-Schmeling_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Schmeling-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> while common practice theory would advise against or rule out the progression on the basis of all the chords being sevenths and thus <a href=\"/wiki/Consonance_and_dissonance\" title=\"Consonance and dissonance\">dissonant</a>.\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.png/220px-Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"35\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.png/330px-Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.png/440px-Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"969\" data-file-height=\"156\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Accompaniment acceptable in the Berklee method<sup id=\"cite_ref-Schmeling_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Schmeling-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> but not in common practice theory. <span class=\"unicode haudio\"><span class=\"fn\"><span style=\"white-space:nowrap\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.mid\" title=\"About this sound\"><img alt=\"About this sound\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/11px-Loudspeaker.svg.png\" width=\"11\" height=\"11\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/17px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Loudspeaker.svg/22px-Loudspeaker.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"20\" data-file-height=\"20\" /></a>&#160;</span><a href=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/43/Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.mid\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Berklee method accompaniment example.mid\">Play</a></span>&#160;<small class=\"metadata audiolinkinfo\" style=\"cursor:help;\">(<a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Media_help\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wikipedia:Media help\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">help</span></a>\u00b7<a href=\"/wiki/File:Berklee_method_accompaniment_example.mid\" title=\"File:Berklee method accompaniment example.mid\"><span style=\"cursor:help;\">info</span></a>)</small></span></div></div></div>\n<p>The following quote from <a href=\"/wiki/Branford_Marsalis\" title=\"Branford Marsalis\">Branford Marsalis</a>, may exemplify how Berklee also differs from traditional jazz: \"Berklee has its own system of doing things, the Berklee way, the Berklee method. They basically say that when you write things that are theoretically against the Berklee method, then they're incorrect. Even if they sound great. Musically they sound great, but theoretically it's wrong, so it's wrong. Which is not the purpose of music. Music theories are just theories.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Berklee_method&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Four_note_group\" title=\"Four note group\">Four note group</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Kod%C3%A1ly_Method\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Kod\u00e1ly Method\">Kod\u00e1ly Method</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Berklee_method&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Hazell, Ed, and Lee Eliot Berk. <i>Berklee: the First Fifty Years</i>. Boston: Berklee Publications, 1995. Print. P. 10 quoted at \"<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://library.berklee.edu/archives\">Berklee Library: Archives</a>\", <i>Berklee.edu</i>. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://library.berklee.edu/archives_content/schillinger_house/index.html\">Pop up</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20110719150409/http://library.berklee.edu/archives_content/schillinger_house/index.html\">Archived</a> July 19, 2011, at the <a href=\"/wiki/Wayback_Machine\" title=\"Wayback Machine\">Wayback Machine</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Schmeling-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Schmeling_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Schmeling_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Schmeling, Paul (2006). <i>Berklee Music Theory - Book 2</i>, p.34. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-87639-066-1\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-87639-066-1\">0-87639-066-1</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">David Andrew Ake (2002). <i>Jazz Cultures</i>, p.144. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-520-22889-8\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-520-22889-8\">0-520-22889-8</a>.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<div role=\"navigation\" class=\"navbox\" aria-labelledby=\"Music_methods\" style=\"padding:3px\"><table class=\"nowraplinks collapsible autocollapse navbox-inner\" style=\"border-spacing:0;background:transparent;color:inherit\"><tbody><tr><th scope=\"col\" class=\"navbox-title\" colspan=\"2\"><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Music_methods\" title=\"Template:Music methods\"><abbr title=\"View this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk\"><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Template_talk:Music_methods&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Template talk:Music methods (page does not exist)\"><abbr title=\"Discuss this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">t</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-edit\"><a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Music_methods&amp;action=edit\"><abbr title=\"Edit this template\" style=\";;background:none transparent;border:none;-moz-box-shadow:none;-webkit-box-shadow:none;box-shadow:none; padding:0;\">e</abbr></a></li></ul></div><div id=\"Music_methods\" style=\"font-size:114%;margin:0 4em\"><a href=\"/wiki/Method_(music)\" title=\"Method (music)\">Music methods</a></div></th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" class=\"navbox-list navbox-odd hlist\" style=\"width:100%;padding:0px\"><div style=\"padding:0em 0.25em\">\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Flute_method\" title=\"Flute method\">Flute</a></li>\n<li>General\n<ul><li><a class=\"mw-selflink selflink\">Berklee method</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Kod%C3%A1ly_Method\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Kod\u00e1ly Method\">Kod\u00e1ly Method</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Orff_